        html: '<p>Tron represented an early and sophisticated example of a phenomenon that would become standard practice in the 1990s: the simultaneous release of a film and its arcade tie-in, with the game cabinet functioning as interactive advertising for the film. Disney and Atari coordinated the Tron release specifically to ensure that the arcade game would be present in or adjacent to cinemas showing the film during its summer 1982 run. The cabinet art was part of this coordination: it reproduced the film\'s visual identity faithfully enough to be immediately recognisable to anyone who had seen promotional material for the movie.</p><p>The challenge for the cabinet artists was adapting the film\'s vector-influenced CGI aesthetic — which was itself a relatively new visual language in 1982 — to the painted medium of arcade cabinet art. The solution was to emphasise the characteristic elements most legible at cabinet scale: the glowing blue grid lines, the geometric helmet designs, the light cycle forms. These elements were simplified and stylised relative to their film versions, but retained the essential visual signature that made Tron\'s aesthetic recognisable.</p>',
